  [0:00 - Introduction]

  Host: "Hi everyone! Today, we are going to do something big. We are going to build a
  professional-grade microservices system from scratch.

  Now, you might be wondering: 'What is a microservice?' Imagine you are building a giant Lego
  castle. Instead of making the whole castle out of one massive piece of plastic, you build it
  using smaller, separate blocks—one for the tower, one for the gate, and one for the walls. If
   the tower breaks, you don't have to throw away the whole castle; you just fix the tower.

  That’s exactly what we’re doing with our code. We are building a product system—kind of like
  a mini version of Amazon. We'll have separate services for products, reviews, and
  recommendations.

  By the end of this video, you'll have a system that is secure, fast, and can handle a lot of
  users. We are starting with this: an empty folder. No code, no configuration, nothing. Let’s
  dive in!"

  [1:30 - The Toolbox: What we need]

  Host: "Before we write a single line of code, we need our tools. Think of this as gathering
  your ingredients before baking a cake.

  First, we need Java 21. Java is the language we're using. Version 21 is the latest and
  greatest, making our code faster and cleaner.

  Second, we need an IDE. I'm using IntelliJ IDEA. This is basically a super-powered text
  editor that helps us find mistakes as we type.

  Third, we need Docker. Docker is a tool that lets us run databases and message brokers—like
  MongoDB and RabbitMQ—without having to install them directly on our Windows or Mac. It puts
  them in 'containers' so they don't mess up our computer.

  And finally, we'll use Maven. Maven is like a project manager. It keeps track of all the
  libraries we use so we don't have to download them manually.

  Once you have those installed, you're ready to go. Let's start building."

  [3:00 - Phase 1: The Project Skeleton]

  Host: "Step one. Let's create our project folder. I'll call mine base_project_1.

  Inside this folder, we aren't just making one project; we are making a 'Multi-Module
  project.' This means we have one big umbrella project that holds several smaller projects
  inside it.

  I'm going to create a few folders first.
  First, api. This will hold our 'contracts'—basically the rules and data formats that all our
  services must agree on.
  Second, util. This is for helper code that every service might need.
  Third, microservices. This is where the actual 'brains' of our system will live.
  Fourth, spring-cloud. This is for the 'infrastructure'—the parts that manage traffic and
  security.

  Why do it this way? Because it keeps things organized. If you put everything in one folder,
  it becomes a giant mess very quickly.

  Now, I'll create a pom.xml file in the root folder. This is the master configuration file for
   Maven. I'm telling Maven: 'Hey, these folders I just created are actually modules of one big
   system.'

  When you run a build, Maven will now know to look into all these folders and compile them
  together. You should see a green checkmark in IntelliJ letting you know the project structure
   is valid."

  [6:00 - Phase 2: The Shared Language (The API Module)]

  Host: "Now, let's go into the api folder.

  In a microservices world, services need to talk to each other. But if the Product service
  speaks Spanish and the Review service speaks French, they won't understand each other.

  So, we create the api module as our 'Shared Language.'

  I'm going to create a package called se.magnus.api. Inside here, I'll create a few DTOs (Data
   Transfer Objects). A DTO is just a simple Java record—like a Product record with a name, a
  description, and a price. It's just a way to move data from point A to point B.

  I'm also creating Interfaces. An interface is like a blueprint. I'll create a ProductService
  interface that says: 'Anyone who wants to be a Product Service must be able to find a product
   by its ID.'

  We aren't writing the logic yet—just the blueprint. This way, other services know exactly
  what to expect when they call the Product service.

  Next, let's jump into the util folder. I'll create a GlobalControllerExceptionHandler. This
  is like a safety net. If something goes wrong anywhere in our system—like a user searching
  for a product that doesn't exist—this piece of code catches the error and sends back a nice,
  clean message instead of a scary wall of technical text.

  Now our foundation is set. We have our rules in api and our safety net in util. Next, let's
  build our first real service."

  [10:00 - Phase 3: The Product Service (Our First Brain)]

  Host: "Let's move into microservices/product-service. This service is responsible for
  managing our products.

  First, we need a place to store the data. We're using MongoDB. MongoDB is a 'NoSQL' database,
   which means it stores data like documents—kind of like folders with papers in them—rather
  than rigid tables. This makes it very flexible.

  I'm going to create a Product entity. This is the version of the product that lives inside
  the database.

  Wait! You'll notice the database entity and the API DTO are slightly different. To move data
  between them, I'll use a tool called MapStruct. MapStruct is like an automatic translator.
  Instead of writing ten lines of code to copy a name from the Entity to the DTO, MapStruct
  does it in one line.

  Now, let's make it Reactive. We are using Spring WebFlux.

  Usually, when a program asks a database for data, it stops and waits until the data arrives.
  This is called 'blocking.' But in a reactive system, the program says: 'Here is my request.
  Let me know when the data is ready; I'll be doing other things in the meantime.' This is
  called 'non-blocking.' It allows our service to handle thousands of users at once without
  slowing down.

  I'll implement the ProductService interface we made earlier. I'll write a method to save a
  product and a method to find one.

  The result? We can now start this service, and it can save and retrieve products from
  MongoDB. It's a simple start, but it's the core of our whole system."

