   files live. When the services start, they call the Config Server, grab their settings, and
  apply them. If we change a file in the repo, the services can update themselves without even
  restarting!

  Second: Event-Driven Messaging.

  Sometimes, services need to talk without waiting for an answer. For example, if a product's
  price changes, the Recommendation service needs to know.

  Instead of the Product service calling the Recommendation service directly, it sends a
  'Message' to a broker—we can use RabbitMQ or Kafka.

  The Product service just shouts: 'Hey, Product X changed!' into the broker. The
  Recommendation service is listening and says: 'Oh! I heard that. I'll update my records.'
  This is called 'Asynchronous Communication,' and it makes the system incredibly fast because
  services don't have to wait for each other."

